<font color="#FF0000">A REMEMBERANCE BY ANON</font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr 30 14:50:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I recieve this Anon e-mail just in this last couple of minutes. I think it is self explanatory what it is about.<br><br>
Photo: see this? That small black dot is me. <br>
These other dots are my parents. We are <br>
part of a larger picture of panic. The metallic <br>
smell of riots &amp; gunpowder make gray days <br>
of our last three. We make plans to evacuate. <br>
Grandmother is supremely confident her <br>
contact will come through, so declines ours. <br>
Just to be sure, she cuts my father’s head <br>
out of family photos. A university professor <br>
is a fine catch, but family members are a <br>
consolation prize. Cousin came to the <br>
airport two days in a row with the rest of us, <br>
but gave up on the third. Instead he goes to <br>
a friend’s to study for a math test, as if the <br>
war was not coming to a close here. Third <br>
time is a charm, even in Saigon. Even in war. <br>
I am slung across my father’s chest as we <br>
move toward the C-14. Soldiers rip out seats <br>
and toss them in a pile outside the cargo door <br>
to make room. Who knows where we are going. <br>
A UPI correspondent snaps a photo from the <br>
air tower. This one. We bring with us in our one <br>
alloted suitcase: glass jars of baby food, one <br>
change of clothes, photos from what would <br>
become &quot;before.&quot; We leave: one maternal <br>
grandmother, an uncle, two aunts, three cousins, <br>
extended family, everything we own, home, <br>
certainty, trust.<br><br>

<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


